      "title": "Legitimacy and the Moral Imagination of Power: A Historical\u2013Philosophical Inquiry from Weber to Contemporary Humanistic Thought",
      "authors": [
        {
          "name": "Bo\u017cena Iwanowska",
          "authorId": "2259000854"
        }
      ],
      "year": 2025,
      "abstract": "This article offers a historical\u2013philosophical inquiry into political legitimacy as a phenomenon that exceeds formal legality and institutional performance, locating legitimacy within the moral imagination through which societies interpret and justify power. Re-reading Weber\u2019s typology of domination as a humanistic problem of meaning, trust, and binding recognition, the study traces how legitimacy shifts across modern thought from inherited tradition and charismatic belief to rational-legal justification and democratic consent. The analysis integrates classical and contemporary perspectives by treating legitimacy as multidimensional: it rests on lawful acquisition and exercise of power, normative justification of governing rules, and the consent of the governed, while remaining continuously vulnerable to symbolic contestation and ethical evaluation. Special attention is given to the conceptual distinction between legitimacy as a state of recognised authority and legitimisation as an ongoing process of justification, clarification, and public confirmation. The article argues that modern legitimacy is sustained not only by procedures and outcomes but also by the capacity of power to appear morally intelligible\u2014credible in conscience, resonant with shared values, and responsive to demands for dignity and fairness. By framing legitimacy as a moral language and interpretive practice, the study provides an integrative lens for analysing contemporary challenges, including the reconfiguration of authority under digital governance, and shifting regimes of trust.",
